A Road Safety Audit for the intersections of Washington Street (Route 53) at Mutton Lane and
Washington Street (Route 53) at Pleasant Street occurred on Monday, December 15, 2014 in Weymouth,
MA. As indicated in Table 1, the audit team consisted of representatives from the Town of Weymouth,
MassDOT Traffic Engineering & Safety, MassDOT District 6, Central Transportation Planning Staff
(CTPS) and a Town of Weymouth resident. The group observed operations and safety at the two study
intersections and this report documents the audit team’s findings. The RSA agenda can be found in
Appendix A. Contact information for the team members can be found in Appendix B.

The intersection of Washington Street (Route 53) and Pleasant Street in Weymouth was among the
Massachusetts Department of Transportation’s (MassDOT) Top 200 Crash Locations from 2010 – 2012,
ranking at #153 in terms of Equivalent Property Damage Only (EPDO)
evaluates crashes in terms of severity, where fatal crashes are weighted by 10, injury crashes are weighted
by 5 and property damage only or non-reported is weighted by 1.

Improvements and Coordination Study” for the intersections and roadway between Washington Street
(Route 53) at Mutton Lane and Washington Street (Route 53) at Pleasant Street. The study included
traffic counts from June 2009 and examined six (6) alternatives within the study area. The study
recommended that an exclusive left-turn lane for westbound traveling vehicles at the Washington Street

The Road Safety Audit (RSA) is one of the first steps in this design process as well as a necessary step for
the project to be eligible to receive Highway Safety Improvement Program (HSIP) federal funds for
construction. The goal of this RSA is to identify potential safety issues that can be addressed with short-
term improvements prior to construction and long-term improvements that can be incorporated into the
design. All improvements should adhere to the MassDOT guidelines for intersection design.
The RSA is a collaborative process by state, municipal, law enforcement, public works, and design
consultants. The process involves conducting a meeting to discuss current crash data and safety issues at
the site, visiting the site to discuss possible solutions that would improve safety, and preparing a written
report that outlines the safety issues discussed along with the costs, timeline, and agency responsibility for

direction through the project area. Route 53 is designated as a north-south route, however, and
northbound is to the west and southbound is to the east. West of Mutton Lane and east of Pleasant Street,
Washington Street is a two-lane roadway with one travel lane in each direction. Approaching the two

Road Safety Audit—Washington Street (Route 53) at Mutton Lane; Washington Street (Route 53) at
Washington Street is striped for two lanes in each direction with one foot shoulders. The intersections are
separated by approximately 800 feet where there are a number of commercial site driveways on both sides
of the roadway. Washington Street serves approximately 17,000 vehicles per day west of Mutton Lane;
approximately 10,500 vehicles per day between Mutton Lane and Pleasant Street; and approximately
15,000 vehicles per day east of Pleasant Street. The speed limit on Washington Street in the vicinity of
the intersections is 35 mph. The roadway is maintained by MassDOT.
Mutton Lane is classified as a local roadway that runs in a general north-south direction with one lane in
each direction for a total length of approximately 0.55 miles. The roadway has both its northern and
southern termini as intersections with Pleasant Street, the northern terminus as a “Y”-type intersection
north of Washington Street and the southern terminus as a “T”-type intersection south of Washington
Street. The intersection of Washington Street at Mutton Lane is a four-way intersection. Mutton Lane
has a truck exclusion for vehicles over 2 ½ tons south of Washington Street. The land use on Mutton
Lane is almost exclusively residential. Mutton Lane serves approximately 4,500 vehicles per day and
there is no posted speed limit. The roadway is maintained by the Town of Weymouth.
Pleasant Street is classified as an urban minor arterial that runs in a general north-south direction through
the project area. The roadway has its southern terminus at Main Street (Route 18) in Weymouth and its
northern terminus at Jackson Square, at the intersection with Broad Street and Commercial Street in
Weymouth. Pleasant Street is one lane in each direction, however widens to accommodate two approach
lanes at the intersection with Washington Street. Pleasant Street is primarily residential with some
commercial uses. Pleasant Street serves approximately 16,500 vehicles per day and the speed limit is 30
mph. The roadway is maintained by the Town of Weymouth.
Nitsch Engineering evaluated the last three years of available crash data (2010 – 2012) from the Town of
Weymouth police records to establish some of the existing safety concerns at the two intersections.
For the Washington Street at Pleasant Street intersection, a total of 54 crashes were reported over the
three-year period. Of the crashes, 20% were personal injury only. A majority of the crashes (59%) were
angle type due to a failure to yield while executing a left-turn. Crashes typically occurred mid-day or
during the peak hours, with the majority of crashes (61%) occurring during daylight hours and/or during
dry conditions. Crashes exhibited no discernable pattern between day of the week or month of the year.
For the Washington Street at Mutton Lane intersection, a total of 21 crashes were reported over the three-
year period. Of the crashes, 24% were personal injury only. Approximately 67% of the crashes were
angle type due to failure to yield while executing left-turn. Most of the angle crashes involved entering
and exiting the existing gas station located in the southwest corner of the intersection. The majority of the
crashes (62%) occurred during the daylight and/or during dry conditions. Crashes exhibited no
discernable pattern between day of the week or month of the year.

Super Petroleum Gas Station presents potential safety concerns with respect to vehicles
entering and exiting the site. The orientation of the gas station pumps causes vehicles
entering the gas station from Mutton Lane to be angled northwest when exiting the
Washington Street curb cut. This creates challenges for vehicles making a right-turn
from the station and may encourage left-turns at this location onto Washington Street.
